                    <msContents>
                        <summary>The second volume of a five-volume set containing stories from the
                            Arabian Nights and other sources.</summary>
                        <msItem xml:id="manuscript_13835-item1">
                            <title xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" key="work_700">Alf laylah
                                wa-laylah</title>
                            <title xml:lang="ar">الف ليلة وليلة؛ حكاية الملك ازاد بخت مع العشرة
                                وزراء وابن الملك يخبر بالبيان؛ خبر حيقار الحكيم الفيلسوف وزير
                                سنحاريب الملك ونادان ابن اخته؛ خبر الملك سابور وما جرى له مع الثلاثة
                                الحكماء</title>
                            <title xml:lang="en" type="supplied">A Thousand and One Nights</title>
                            <textLang mainLang="ar">Arabic</textLang>
                            <note><p>For the other volumes of the set, see <ref
                                        target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_13834"
                                        >Arabic MS 134</ref> (Vol. 1), <ref
                                        target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_13836"
                                        >Arabic MS 136</ref> (Vol. 3), <ref
                                        target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_13837"
                                        >Arabic MS 137</ref> (Vol. 4), <ref
                                        target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_13838"
                                        >Arabic MS 138</ref> (Vol. 5).</p></note>

                            <msItem xml:id="Arabic_MS_135-item1-item1">
                                <locus from="3" to="100"/>
                                <title xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc"/>
                                <title xml:lang="ar">خبر الملك ازاد بخت مع العشرة وزراء وابن الملك
                                    يخبر بالبيان</title>
                                <title xml:lang="en"/>
                                <note><p>The story of the King Azād Bakht, of his son who was
                                        imprisoned, and of his ten viziers. The story is divided
                                        into eleven sections representing the eleven stories told by
                                        the King's son in his trial of eleven days (Mingana).</p>
                                    <p>Cf. Manchester John Rylands Library, Arabic MS 557, folios
                                        1-44a.</p></note>
                            </msItem>

                            <msItem xml:id="Arabic_MS_135-item1-item2">
                                <locus from="101" to="130"/>
                                <title xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc"/>
                                <title xml:lang="ar">خبر حيقار الحكيم الفيلسوف وزير يسنحاريب الملك
                                    ونادان ابن اخته</title>
                                <title xml:lang="en">The story of Aḥīḳār, the vizier of
                                    Sennacherib</title>
                                <note><p>In phraseology the story differs somewhat from that edited
                                        in 1913 by <ref
                                            target="https://archive.org/details/HarrisConybeareLewis1913TheStoryOfAhikar.../page/n5/mode/2up"
                                            >Agnes Smith Lewis in "The Story of Aḥiḳar,"</ref> (cf.
                                        pp. 1-32).</p>
                                </note>
                            </msItem>
                            
                            <msItem xml:id="Arabic_MS_135-item1-item3">
                                <locus from="131" to="154"/>
                                <title xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc"/>
                                <title xml:lang="ar">خبر الملك سابور وما جرى له مع الثلاثة حكماء</title>
                                <title xml:lang="en"/>
                                <note><p>The story of King Sapor and of the three wise men.</p></note>
                            </msItem>
                        </msItem>
